1. Collaborative Solution Verification

I first analyzed the logic as if I were working with another developer or AI assistant.

Observations:
The recursive mergeSort structure is correct
The bug is isolated in the merge function
One pointer is incorrectly incremented (j++ instead of i++)
Verified Issue:

The left-side remaining elements loop is incorrect:

while (i < left.length) {
  result.push(left[i]);
  j++; // incorrect
}

This causes:

infinite loop risk OR incorrect merge behavior
corrupted sorting results
Correct understanding:
i tracks left array
j tracks right array
each loop must increment its own pointer
2. Learning Through Alternative Approaches

I tested mental models of merge sort:

Approach A: Standard merge logic
Always consume smallest element
Then append leftovers from left/right
Approach B: Two-pointer validation
i must move only when reading left
j must move only when reading right
Key insight:

Merge sort correctness depends entirely on pointer consistency

So:

wrong pointer increment = broken algorithm
even if recursion is correct
